Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1 & 2: Guard Navigation with a Confirmation Dialog

In your `AppShell.xaml.cs`, override `OnNavigating` and use `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await page.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required for async checks — without it you'll have a race condition.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- Check `ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so this only fires on back navigation.

## 3: Custom "Cancel" Back Button

In `EditProductPage.xaml`, attach a `BackButtonBehavior`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your ViewModel (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating above, so the guard still applies
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

The `TextOverride="Cancel"` replaces the default back arrow with "Cancel" text. The `Command` gives you full control — navigation via `GoToAsync("..")` still flows through `OnNavigating`, so your unsaved-changes guard remains active.
